<paragraph id="8BC53698FFABFFA3E9B11254FB3650F2" blockId="43.[684,1212,1505,1739]" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">
IDENTIFICATION: 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFABFFA3E8F11254FC6E5059" authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1829" box="[924,996,1610,1633]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8AFFABFFA3E8F11254FC6E5059" box="[924,996,1610,1633]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most diverse and widely distributed bat genus with 126 species recognized (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFABFFA3E8591291FB82509F" author="Burgin, C. J. &amp; J. P. Colella &amp; P. L. Kahn &amp; N. S. Upham" box="[820,1032,1679,1703]" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref33565" refString="Burgin, C. J., J. P. Colella, P. L. Kahn, and N. S. Upham. 2018. How many species of mammals are there? Journal of Mammalogy 99: 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="2018">Burgin et al., 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The taxonomy and systematics of the genus, especially in the
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC53698FFACFFA4EB0114FCFEF852A0" blockId="44.[108,638,225,1176]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">
New World, is confused and controversial (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EB01151DFF7C5724" author="LaVal, R. K." box="[108,246,259,284]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 54" refId="ref38194" refString="LaVal, R. K. 1973. A revision of the Neotropical bats of the genus Myotis. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County 15: 1 - 54." type="journal article" year="1973">LaVal, 1973</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EA6A151DFDFD5724" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; J. A. de Oliveira" box="[263,631,259,284]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="789 - 802" refId="ref39702" refString="Moratelli, R., and J. A. de Oliveira. 2011. Morphometric and morphological variation in South American populations of Myotis albescens (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Zoologia 28: 789 - 802." type="journal article" year="2011">Moratelli and de Oliveira, 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EB011538FEDD5706" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Peracchi &amp; J. A. de Oliveira" box="[108,343,294,318]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="41 - 54" refId="ref39827" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Peracchi, and J. A. de Oliveira. 2011 a. Morphometric and morphological variation in Myotis simus Thomas (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae), with an appraisal of the identity of Myotis guaycuru Proenca based on the analysis of the type material. Zootaxa 2985: 41 - 54." type="journal article" year="2011">
Moratelli et al., 2011 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EA261538FEDD5706" author="Larsen, P. A. &amp; M. R. Marchan-Rivadeneira &amp; R. J. Baker" box="[331,343,294,318]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="315 - 339" refId="ref38081" refString="Larsen, P. A., M. R. Marchan-Rivadeneira, and R. J. Baker. 2013. Speciation dynamics of the fruit-eating bats (genus Artibeus): with evidence of ecological divergence in Central American populations. In R. A. Adams and S. C. Pedersen (editors), Bat evolution, ecology, and conservation: 315 - 339. New York: Springer." type="book chapter" year="2013">a</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
,b, 2013; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EADE1538FF595758" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; D. E. Wilson" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="115 - 121" refId="ref39741" refString="Moratelli, R., and D. E. Wilson. 2011. The identity of Myotis punensis (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Zoologia 28: 115 - 121." type="journal article" year="2011">Moratelli and Wilson, 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EBB01557FE165758" author="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R. &amp; P. A. Larsen &amp; C. J. Phillips &amp; R. E. Strauss &amp; R. J. Baker" box="[221,412,328,352]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="623 - 634" refId="ref39181" refString="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R., P. A. Larsen, C. J. Phillips, R. E. Strauss, and R. J. Baker. 2012. On the association between environmental gradients and skull size variation in the great fruit-eating bat, Artibeus lituratus (Chiroptera: Phyllostomidae). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 105: 623 - 634." type="journal article" year="2012">Larsen et al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EACB1556FED857BB" author="Mantilla-Meluk, H. &amp; J. Munoz-Garay" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="60 - 70" refId="ref39094" refString="Mantilla-Meluk, H., and J. Munoz-Garay. 2014. Biogeography and taxonomic status of Myotis keaysi pilosatibialis LaVal 1973 (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Zootaxa 3793: 60 - 70." type="journal article" year="2014">Mantilla-Meluk and Muñoz-Garay, 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Recently, several studies have attempted to clarify the taxonomy of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFACFFA4EB0115AEFEAA57FF" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[108,288,432,455]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8AFFACFFA4EB0115AEFEAA57FF" box="[108,288,432,455]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Myotis nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EA8615B1FF2B57D2" author="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R. &amp; P. A. Larsen &amp; C. J. Phillips &amp; R. E. Strauss &amp; R. J. Baker" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="623 - 634" refId="ref39181" refString="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R., P. A. Larsen, C. J. Phillips, R. E. Strauss, and R. J. Baker. 2012. On the association between environmental gradients and skull size variation in the great fruit-eating bat, Artibeus lituratus (Chiroptera: Phyllostomidae). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 105: 623 - 634." type="journal article" year="2012">Larsen et al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EBC615CFFE0D57D2" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[171,391,465,490]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EAFC15CFFF2E5434" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; D. E. Wilson" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="533 - 542" refId="ref39773" refString="Moratelli, R., and D. E. Wilson. 2014. A second record of Myotis diminutus (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae): its bearing on the taxonomy of the species and discrimination from M. nigricans. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 127: 533 - 542." type="journal article" year="2014">Moratelli and Wilson, 2014</bibRefCitation>
). One of the results of these revisions was the recognition of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFACFFA4EA5F1609FE685416" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1914" box="[306,482,535,558]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caucensis">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8AFFACFFA4EA5F1609FE685416" box="[306,482,535,558]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Myotis caucensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species where previously it had been regarded as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFACFFA4EA3B1645FDF6544B" baseAuthorityName="Cornalia" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[342,636,603,627]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="nigricans" subSpecies="osculatii">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8AFFACFFA4EA3B1645FDF6544B" box="[342,636,603,627]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Myotis nigricans osculatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EB1E1663FE9B54AD" author="Wilson, D. E." box="[115,273,637,661]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="468 - 481" refId="ref44630" refString="Wilson, D. E. 2008 b (&quot; 2007 &quot;). Genus Myotis Kaup, 1829. In A. L. Gardner (editor), Mammals of South America, vol. 1: Marsupials, xenarthrans, shrews, and bats: 468 - 481. Chicago: University of Chicago Press." type="book chapter" year="2008">Wilson, 2008b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EA771663FE7D54AD" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[282,503,637,661]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFACFFA4E9651660FF0F548F" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1914" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caucensis">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8AFFACFFA4E9651660FF0F548F" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">M. caucensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs along the intermontane valleys of the Andes in 
<collectingCountry id="F36D7608FFACFFA4EBB716DCFECD54E2" box="[218,327,706,730]" name="Colombia" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F36D7608FFACFFA4EAC116DCFD8354E2" box="[428,521,706,730]" name="Ecuador" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F36D7608FFACFFA4E92416DCFDF654E1" box="[585,636,706,729]" name="Peru" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Peru</collectingCountry>
and the adjacent Amazon lowlands across an elevational range from ca. 
<quantity id="4C829B7DFFACFFA4EAE61718FDAC5526" box="[395,550,774,798]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="0.2" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" unit="m" value="1400.0" valueMax="2600.0" valueMin="200.0">200 to 2600 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4E9581718FF295579" author="LaVal, R. K." pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 54" refId="ref38194" refString="LaVal, R. K. 1973. A revision of the Neotropical bats of the genus Myotis. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County 15: 1 - 54." type="journal article" year="1973">LaVal, 1973</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EBDC1736FE155579" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[177,415,808,833]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
). No subspecies are currently recognized in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D1BFFACFFA4EA061752FF5955BD" authority="(Moratelli et al., 2013)" baseAuthorityName="Moratelli" baseAuthorityYear="2013" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caucensis">
<emphasis id="B90EEA8AFFACFFA4EA061752FE7B555B" box="[363,497,844,867]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">M. caucensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EA901755FF4155BD" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Our Mayo River basin voucher specimens exhibit the diagnostic characteristics of the species: medium-size (FA 36.0–38.5 mm); dorsal pelage silky and unicolored; a fringe of hairs lacking along the trailing edge of the uropatagium; sagittal crest absent; and frontals not steeply sloping (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEB4B69FFACFFA4EBF01025FE08526B" author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[157,386,1083,1107]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Measurements of our specimens fall within the range of measurements reported for the species.
</paragraph>
